{"title_page": "S. K. Gurunathan", "text_new": "{{infobox person\n|name =S. K. Gurunathan\n|birth_date =August 1, 1908\n|death_date={{death date and age|1966|5|5|1908|8|1}}\n|occupation=Sports journalist\n}}\n'''S. K. Gurunathan''' (1 August 1908 \u2013 5 May 1966) was a sports journalist and one of the pioneers of [[cricket statistics]] in India.\n\nGurunathan started his journalistic career in the advertisement section of ''[[The Hindu]]'' in 1928. He became a reporter in 1938 and from 1958 till his death, was the sports editor. He founded the ''Madras Sports Annual'' which covered local cricket and other sports in the 1940s. While at ''The Hindu'', he started the magazine ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'' which ran for about twenty years and ceased publication due to labour troubles soon after his death. Gurunathan was the first Honorary Cricket Statistician for the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]], serving in that post from 1949-50 till his death.\n\nGurunathan founded the annual ''[[Indian Cricket (annual)|Indian Cricket]]'' in 1946 on the same lines as the ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]'' and remained its editor till his death. He also regularly contributed to the Indian section of ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]''. He covered more than 50 Test matches including the Indian tours of Australia in 1947-48, England in 1952 and Pakistan in 1954-55, and reported the 1961-62 [[English cricket team|MCC]] tour of India for ''[[The Times]]''. He authored the books ''12 years of Ranji Trophy'' and three volumes of ''Story of the Tests''. Gurunathan became the Founder-President of the Madras Sports Writers Club in 1963-64.\n\nHe was a stylish wicket keeper in his youth and represented the Indians in the Madras Presidency matches. In the Madras League matches, he represented Sundar C.C. He died a few months before he was due to retire from ''The Hindu''.\n\n==References==\n* Sudhir Vaidya, ''Guru'', Anka - the official journal of the Association of the Cricket Statisticians and Scorers of India, July\u2013September 2001, pp.&nbsp;3\u20135\n\n==External links==\n*[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/39/39075/39075.html Cricketarchive profile]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gurunathan, S. K.}}\n[[Category:Cricket historians and writers|Gurunathan, S.K.]]\n[[Category:Indian sports journalists]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Cricket statisticians]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person\n|name =S. K. Gurunathan\n|birth_date =August 1, 1908\n|death_date={{death date and age|1966|5|5|1908|8|1}}\n|occupation=Sports journalist\n}}\n'''S. K. Gurunathan''' (1 August 1908 \u2013 5 May 1966) was a sports journalist and one of the pioneers of [[cricket statistics]] in India.\n\nGurunathan started his journalistic career in the advertisement section of ''[[The Hindu]]'' in 1928. He became a reporter in 1938 and from 1958 till his death, was the sports editor. He founded the ''Madras Sports Annual'' which covered local cricket and other sports in the 1940s. While at ''The Hindu'', he started the magazine ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'' which ran for about twenty years and ceased publication due to labour troubles soon after his death. Gurunathan was the first Honorary Cricket Statistician for the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]], serving in that post from 1949-50 till his death.\n\nGurunathan founded the annual ''[[Indian Cricket (annual)|Indian Cricket]]'' in 1946 on the same lines as the ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]]'' and remained its editor till his death. He also regularly contributed to the Indian section of ''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]''. He covered more than 50 Test matches including the Indian tours of Australia in 1947-48, England in 1952 and Pakistan in 1954-55, and reported the 1961-62 [[English cricket team|MCC]] tour of India for ''[[The Times]]''. He authored the books ''12 years of Ranji Trophy'' and three volumes of ''Story of the Tests''. Gurunathan became the Founder-President of the Madras Sports Writers Club in 1963-64.\n\nHe was a stylish wicket keeper in his youth and represented the Indians in the Madras Presidency matches. In the Madras League matches, he represented Sundar C.C. He died a few months before he was due to retire from ''The Hindu''.\n\n==References==\n* Sudhir Vaidya, ''Guru'', Anka - the official journal of the Association of the Cricket Statisticians and Scorers of India, July-September 2001, pp. 3-5\n\n==External links==\n*[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/39/39075/39075.html Cricketarchive profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gurunathan, S. K.}}\n[[Category:Cricket historians and writers|Gurunathan, S.K.]]\n[[Category:Indian sports journalists]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Cricket statisticians]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S._K._Gurunathan"}
{"title_page": "John Hedgecoe", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n'''John Hedgecoe''' (24 March 1932&nbsp;\u2013 3 June 2010)<ref name=\"guardian obit\">{{cite web |last=Hopkinson |first=Amanda |title=John Hedgecoe obituary |work=Culture: Art & Design: Photography |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 June 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/jun/29/john-hedgecoe-obituary |accessdate=2013-08-12 }}</ref> was a British photographer and author of over 30 books on photography.<ref name=\"BJP\">{{Cite web |last=Bainbridge |first=Simon |url=http://www.bjp-online.com/british-journal-of-photography/news/1653040/the-taught-world-photograph |title=The man who taught the world to photograph |publisher=[[British Journal of Photography]] |accessdate=12 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610225441/http://www.bjp-online.com/british-journal-of-photography/news/1653040/the-taught-world-photograph |archivedate=10 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He established the photography department in 1965 at the [[Royal College of Art]], where he was Professor from 1975 to 1994 and Professor Emeritus until his death.<ref name=\"guardian obit\"/> He was also Pro-Rector of the college from 1981 to 1994.<ref name=\"RCA retrospective\">{{cite web |title=John Hedgecoe Comes \u2018Home\u2019 in RCA Exhibition |publisher=[[Royal College of Art]] |date=16 July 2014 |url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/news/john-hedgecoe-comes-home-rca-exhibition |accessdate=2016-01-03 }}</ref> His photographs appear in permanent collections at the New York [[Museum of Modern Art]] and London's [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref name=\"BJP\"/>\n\n== Early life ==\nHedgecoe was born in [[Brentford]], [[Middlesex]]. Born the son of a banker, John Hedgecoe received his first camera from his father at the age of 14. Hedgecoe and his family were evacuated during [[World War II]]. They settled in Gulval, a village near [[Penzance]] in [[Cornwall]] where he attended the local school.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Hedgecoe Obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/jun/29/john-hedgecoe-obituary|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nHedgecoe attended [[Guildford School of Art]] (now [[University for the Creative Arts]]), while also completing his National Service with the RAF. During his service with the RAF, Hedgecoe experimented with aerial photographic surveys of bomb damage from the war.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Professor John Hedgecoe|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/7815174/Professor-John-Hedgecoe.html|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> In 1957, he started work as a staff photographer at ''[[Queen (magazine)|Queen]]'' magazine, working there until 1972.<ref name=Independent/><ref name=\"guardian obit\"/>\n\n==Creative work==\nIn the main, Hedgecoe's works are focused on artists and writers. He said: \"A good portrait photograph should try to tell us something about the subject's character, for the portrait is a visual biography in a sense.\" One of Hedgecoe's books was a  ''Henry Spencer Moore'', published in 1968.{{cn|date=March 2018}} Most Photographs by John Hedgecoe are stored at the [[Sainsbury Centre for Visual Arts]] in [[Norwich]].<ref name=Independent>{{cite web|last=Cripps|first=Charlotte|title=John Hedgecoe: Artists off their guard|date=21 June 2011|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/john-hedgecoe-artists-off-their-guard-2300639.html|accessdate=1 February 2018|website=Independent}}</ref>\n\n==Postage stamps==\n\nHedgecoe\u2019s profile shot of the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]], taken by him in June 1967, was used by [[Arnold Machin]] to make a plaster version. Once the plaster version was produced, Hedgecoe photographed it for the stamp image. It is one of the most-reproduced images, with over 200 billion copies sold.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/most-reproduced-photographic-portrait-ever-7454145|title='Most reproduced photographic portrait ever' goes on show in Kensington|last=Cooper|first=Goolistan|date=2014-07-18|work=getwestlondon|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Stamp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/06/breaking-news-royal-stamp-photographer-dies-today/|title=Royal stamp photographer dies today|date=7 June 2010|publisher=World Stamp News|accessdate=16 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122145238/http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/06/breaking-news-royal-stamp-photographer-dies-today/|archivedate=22 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1960, Hedgecoe married Julia Mardon. The couple has three children: Sebastian, Dolly and Auberon.<ref name=Independent/>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Manual of Photography'' [[Focal Press]], 1977, {{ISBN|0240509579}}\n* ''John Hedgecoe's Nude Photography''  Simon Schuster, 1984  {{ISBN|0-671-52326-0}}\n* ''John Hedgecoe's Practical Landscape Photography'' [[Ebury Press]], 1988  {{ISBN|0-85223-651-4}}\n* ''The Photographer\u2019s Handbook'' Alfred A. Knopf, 1992, {{ISBN|0679742042}}\n* ''Breakfast with Dolly'', novel (1996)\n* ''John Hedgecoe's 35mm Photography'' Collins & Brown, 1999, {{ISBN|9781855857148}}\n* ''The New Manual of Photography'' [[DK Publishing]], 2003\n* ''John Hedgecoe's Complete Guide to Black White Photography'' Sterling, 2005, {{ISBN|1402728123}}\n* ''How to Take Great Photographs'' Collins & Brown, 2005, {{ISBN|1843403307}}\n* ''The Art of Digital Photography'' [[Dorling Kindersley]], 2009, {{ISBN|9781405340939}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hedgecoe, John}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:British photographers]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers on photographic techniques]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n\n{{UK-photographer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n'''John Hedgecoe''' (24 March 1932&nbsp;\u2013 3 June 2010)<ref name=\"guardian obit\">{{cite web |last=Hopkinson |first=Amanda |title=John Hedgecoe obituary |work=Culture: Art & Design: Photography |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 June 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/jun/29/john-hedgecoe-obituary |accessdate=2013-08-12 }}</ref> was a British photographer and author of over 30 books on photography.<ref name=\"BJP\">{{Cite web |last=Bainbridge |first=Simon |url=http://www.bjp-online.com/british-journal-of-photography/news/1653040/the-taught-world-photograph |title=The man who taught the world to photograph |publisher=[[British Journal of Photography]] |accessdate=12 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610225441/http://www.bjp-online.com/british-journal-of-photography/news/1653040/the-taught-world-photograph |archivedate=10 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He established the photography department in 1965 at the [[Royal College of Art]], where he was Professor from 1975 to 1994 and Professor Emeritus until his death.<ref name=\"guardian obit\"/> He was also Pro-Rector of the college from 1981 to 1994.<ref name=\"RCA retrospective\">{{cite web |title=John Hedgecoe Comes \u2018Home\u2019 in RCA Exhibition |publisher=[[Royal College of Art]] |date=16 July 2014 |url=http://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/news/john-hedgecoe-comes-home-rca-exhibition |accessdate=2016-01-03 }}</ref> His photographs appear in permanent collections at the New York [[Museum of Modern Art]] and London's [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref name=\"BJP\"/>\n\n== Early life ==\nHedgecoe was born in [[Brentford]], [[Middlesex]]. Born the son of a banker, John Hedgecoe received his first camera from his father at the age of 14. Hedgecoe and his family were evacuated during [[World War II]]. They settled in Gulval, a village near [[Penzance]] in [[Cornwall]] where he attended the local school.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Hedgecoe Obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2010/jun/29/john-hedgecoe-obituary|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nHedgecoe attended [[Guildford School of Art]] (now [[University for the Creative Arts]]), while also completing his National Service with the RAF. During his service with the RAF, Hedgecoe experimented with aerial photographic surveys of bomb damage from the war.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=Professor John Hedgecoe|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/7815174/Professor-John-Hedgecoe.html|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> In 1957, he started work as a staff photographer at ''[[Queen (magazine)|Queen]]'' magazine, working there until 1972.<ref name=Independent/><ref name=\"guardian obit\"/>\n\n==Creative work==\nIn the main, Hedgecoe's works are focused on artists and writers. He said: \"A good portrait photograph should try to tell us something about the subject's character, for the portrait is a visual biography in a sense.\" One of Hedgecoe's books was a  ''Henry Spencer Moore'', published in 1968.{{cn|date=March 2018}} Most Photographs by John Hedgecoe are stored at the [[Sainsbury Centre for Visual Arts]] in [[Norwich]].<ref name=Independent>{{cite web|last=Cripps|first=Charlotte|title=John Hedgecoe: Artists off their guard|date=21 June 2011|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/john-hedgecoe-artists-off-their-guard-2300639.html|accessdate=1 February 2018|website=Independent}}</ref>\n\n==Postage stamps==\n\nHedgecoe\u2019s profile shot of the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]], taken by him in June 1967, was used by [[Arnold Machin]] to make a plaster version. Once the plaster version was produced, Hedgecoe photographed it for the stamp image. It is one of the most-reproduced images, with over 200 billion copies sold.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/whats-on/arts-culture-news/most-reproduced-photographic-portrait-ever-7454145|title='Most reproduced photographic portrait ever' goes on show in Kensington|last=Cooper|first=Goolistan|date=2014-07-18|work=getwestlondon|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Stamp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/06/breaking-news-royal-stamp-photographer-dies-today/|title=Royal stamp photographer dies today|date=7 June 2010|publisher=World Stamp News|accessdate=16 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122145238/http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/06/breaking-news-royal-stamp-photographer-dies-today/|archivedate=22 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1960, Hedgecoe married Julia Mardon. The couple has three children: Sebastian, Dolly and Auberon.<ref name=Independent/>\n\n==Publications==\n* ''Manual of Photography'' [[Focal Press]], 1977, {{ISBN|0240509579}}\n* ''John Hedgecoe's Nude Photography''  Simon Schuster, 1984  {{ISBN|0-671-52326-0}}\n* ''The Photographer\u2019s Handbook'' Alfred A. Knopf, 1992, {{ISBN|0679742042}}\n* ''Breakfast with Dolly'', novel (1996)\n* ''John Hedgecoe's 35mm Photography'' Collins & Brown, 1999, {{ISBN|9781855857148}}\n* ''The New Manual of Photography'' [[DK Publishing]], 2003\n* ''John Hedgecoe's Complete Guide to Black White Photography'' Sterling, 2005, {{ISBN|1402728123}}\n* ''How to Take Great Photographs'' Collins & Brown, 2005, {{ISBN|1843403307}}\n* ''The Art of Digital Photography'' [[Dorling Kindersley]], 2009, {{ISBN|9781405340939}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hedgecoe, John}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:British photographers]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Writers on photographic techniques]]\n[[Cat